VALUES
(42, 4, 8, 66, 22, 9, 9, NULL, 'Worshiping God Alone', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of worshiping God exclusively. In Luke, Jesus asserts that only God should be served, while Revelation reinforces this by instructing to worship God.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 8, 9, 7, 3, 3, NULL, 'Worship and Service to God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of serving God exclusively. Luke 4:8 quotes the command to worship God only, while 1 Samuel 7:3 calls for the removal of foreign gods to serve Him alone.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 9, 40, 4, 5, 6, 'pinnacle of the temple', 'Connection of Temptation Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the temptation of Jesus at a pinnacle of the temple. The devil challenges Jesus to prove his identity as the Son of God by casting himself down, highlighting a direct parallel in the narrative of temptation.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 9, 40, 8, 29, 29, 'If thou be the Son of God', 'Connection of Sonship and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''the Son of God.'' This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' divine authority and the challenges he faces regarding his identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 9, 42, 4, 3, 3, 'If thou be the Son of God', 'Temptations of the Son of God', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge to Jesus'' identity as the Son of God. In each instance, the devil presents a test that questions Jesus'' divine authority and power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 9, 45, 1, 4, 4, 'If thou be the Son of God', 'Connection of Sonship and Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' identity as the ''Son of God.'' In Luke, the challenge to prove His sonship contrasts with Romans, where His divine sonship is affirmed through resurrection power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 9, 14, 3, 4, 4, 'pinnacle of the temple', 'Connection of Temple Imagery', 'This connection highlights the significance of the temple in both passages. The pinnacle of the temple in Luke represents a place of prominence, while the description of the porch in Chronicles emphasizes its grandeur and height.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 9, 18, 2, 6, 6, NULL, 'Testing of Faith and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of testing faith and authority in both passages. In Luke, the challenge to Jesus to cast himself down reflects a test of his divine sonship, while in Job, Satan is given authority over Job''s suffering, testing his faithfulness.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 10, 19, 91, 11, 12, 'He shall give his angels charge over thee', 'Connection of Angelic Protection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine protection through angels. Both passages emphasize that angels are given charge to keep and support individuals in their ways.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 10, 58, 1, 14, 14, 'He shall give his angels charge over thee', 'Angels as Ministering Spirits', 'This connection highlights the role of angels in both passages. Luke 4:10 mentions angels being given charge, while Hebrews 1:14 describes them as ministering spirits for those who will inherit salvation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 10, 47, 11, 14, 14, 'angels', 'Angels and Deception', 'This connection highlights the dual nature of angels in scripture. While Luke 4:10 speaks of angels as protectors, 2 Corinthians 11:14 warns of the deceptive nature of Satan, who masquerades as an angel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 10, 42, 4, 3, 3, 'He shall give his angels charge over thee', 'Connection of Divine Protection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine protection. In Luke 4:10, the promise of angels guarding is contrasted with the devil''s challenge in Luke 4:3, questioning Jesus'' identity and authority as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 10, 42, 4, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Worship and Protection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of worshiping God alone. The reference to angels in the source verse suggests divine protection, which is a theme that supports the call to worship God in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.286, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 11, 19, 91, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Protection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine protection, as they describe how beings will support and prevent harm. The exact phrase ''lest thou dash thy foot against a stone'' appears in both, reinforcing this protective message.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 5, 6, 16, 16, 'Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Connection of Tempting God', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition against tempting God. Luke quotes the command from Deuteronomy, reinforcing the idea that testing God''s patience is forbidden.', 'quotation', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 58, 3, 8, 9, 'Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Temptation of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of temptation directed towards God. Luke 4:12 warns against tempting the Lord, while Hebrews 3:8-9 recalls the Israelites'' provocation of God during their wilderness journey.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 40, 4, 7, 7, 'Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Connection of Jesus'' Response', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' response to temptation by quoting the same command. The phrase ''Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God'' appears in both, illustrating a direct textual link.', 'quotation', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 46, 10, 9, 9, 'Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Tempting the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of not tempting God. Luke 4:12 warns against tempting the Lord, while 1 Corinthians 10:9 specifically mentions tempting Christ, linking the two ideas.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 19, 95, 9, 9, 'thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Temptation of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of testing God. In Luke, Jesus references not tempting God, while Psalms recounts the Israelites testing Him and witnessing His works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 39, 3, 15, 15, 'Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Tempting God in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the act of tempting God. Luke 4:12 directly states, ''Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God,'' while Malachi 3:15 mentions those who ''tempt God.'' This connection highlights a moral warning against challenging divine authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 12, 19, 106, 14, 14, 'thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God', 'Tempting God in the Wilderness', 'Both passages emphasize the act of tempting God, with Luke 4:12 quoting the command against it, while Psalms 106:14 recounts the Israelites'' actions in the wilderness. This connection highlights the theme of testing God''s patience and authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 13, 59, 4, 7, 7, NULL, 'Resisting the Devil', 'This connection highlights the theme of resisting the devil. In both passages, the devil''s departure signifies the effectiveness of resistance, suggesting that submission to God empowers believers to overcome temptation.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 13, 58, 4, 15, 15, NULL, 'Temptation and Infirmities Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of temptation in both passages. Luke 4:13 mentions the devil''s departure after temptation, while Hebrews 4:15 emphasizes that Jesus was tempted in all points, yet remained sinless.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 13, 40, 4, 11, 11, NULL, 'Temptation and Departure of the Devil', 'Both passages emphasize the departure of the devil after temptation. Luke notes that the devil ''departed from him for a season,'' while Matthew states that ''the devil leaveth him.''', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 13, 43, 14, 30, 30, 'the devil had ended all the temptation', 'Temptation and the Prince of World', 'This connection highlights the presence of the devil as a tempter in both passages. In Luke, the devil departs after temptation, while in John, Jesus refers to the ''prince of this world'' coming, indicating ongoing spiritual conflict.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 14, 40, 4, 23, 25, 'fame of him through all the region', 'Jesus'' Fame in Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize the growing fame of Jesus in Galilee. Luke mentions his fame spreading through the region, while Matthew elaborates on the crowds drawn to him for healing and teaching.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 14, 44, 10, 37, 37, 'Galilee', 'Connection of Galilee and Fame', 'This connection highlights the significance of Galilee as the starting point for Jesus'' ministry. Both passages emphasize the spread of Jesus'' fame beginning in Galilee, illustrating its role in the proclamation of his message.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 14, 40, 4, 12, 12, 'into Galilee', 'Connection of Jesus'' Ministry in Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement into Galilee, indicating a significant phase in his ministry. The mention of Galilee in both contexts highlights the geographical focus of Jesus'' early activities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 14, 41, 1, 28, 28, 'fame of him through all the region', 'Fame of Jesus in Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of Jesus'' fame throughout Galilee. The mention of ''fame'' in both verses highlights the impact of his ministry in the region.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
